'''Jodi Grant''' (born March 1968) is the executive director of the [[Afterschool Alliance]], an American not-for-profit organization.<ref name="Afterschool Alliance">{{cite web|title=Offices & Staff|url=http://www.afterschoolalliance.org/aboutUsOffices.cfm|publisher=[[Afterschool Alliance]]|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref> Prior to joining the Afterschool Alliance, Grant was the director of Work and Family Programs for the [[National Partnership for Women and Families]]. She also worked on [[Capitol Hill]] as general counsel to the [[Senate Budget Committee]] and as staff director for the Democratic Steering and Coordination Committee. Grant frequently appears in national media, including [[National Public Radio]], the ''[[Washington Post]]'', the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[Bloomberg Business]]'', and ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=NPR>{{cite web|title=Moms Scramble To Find Afterschool Care|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=112432376|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The secret war on afterschool programs|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/wp/2013/07/15/the-secret-war-on-afterschool-programs/|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Parents Scramble as Ax Falls on After-School Programs|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204660604574372790309436158|publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fewer Home Alone As Census Sees 39% Drop in Latchkey Kids|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-06-11/fewer-home-alone-as-census-sees-39-drop-in-latchkey-kids|publisher=[[Bloomberg Business]]|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=It’s 3 O’Clock. You’re at Work. Where Are Your Kids?|url=http://parenting.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/16/its-3-oclock-youre-at-work-where-are-your-kids/?_r=0|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref>

== Early life and education ==

Grant was born in [[Flushing, Queens, New York]]. She grew up in [[Oyster Bay, New York]], where she attended Oyster Bay High School. She received her B.A. in Sociology with distinction from [[Yale University]] in 1990, where she was elected senior class president. In 1993, Grant received her J.D. from [[Harvard Law School]], where she was elected president (first marshall) of the class of 1993. She also served on the editorial board for the ''Human Rights Journal''.<ref name="HeinOnline">{{citeweb|title=Harvard Human Rights Journal, Volume 5, Spring 1992|url=http://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/hhrj5&div=4&id=&page=|publisher=HeinOnline|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref> Grant, her husband and two children live in [[Bethesda, Maryland]].<ref name="NAA">{{cite web|title=Jodi Grant|url=http://naaweb.org/jodi-grant|publisher=National After-School Association|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref>

== Career ==

Grant worked as the [[general counsel]] for the Democratic Senate Budget Committee from 1994 to 1997. As general counsel, she managed budget bills and reconciliation bills on the floor of  the [[United States Senate]], coordinated closely with Republican staff of the budget committee to develop and implement legislation, and handling all legal and ethical matters.<ref name="NAA" />

From 1997 to 2001, Grant served as the staff director for the Democratic Steering and Coordination Committee, chaired by then-Sen. [[John Kerry]].<ref name="GPO">{{cite web|title=Select and Special Committees of the Senate|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CDIR-1999-06-15/pdf/CDIR-1999-06-15-STATISTICALINFORMATION-2.pdf|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office]]|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref> Her legislative accomplishments include expanded support for the child tax credit, the [[State Children's Health Insurance Program|Children's Health Insurance Program]] and class size reduction. She also served as liaison to the National Governors' Association, where she worked closely with [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] governors.<ref name="NAA" />

Following her tenure as a Senate staffer, Grant joined the [[National Partnership for Women & Families]], formerly the Women’s Legal Defense Fund, serving as Director of Work and Family Programs from 2001 to 2005. Grant worked to protect and expand the ''Family and Medical Leave Act'', and was a member of the team that successfully defended the law before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] in ''Hibbs vs. Nevada Department of Human Resources''.<ref>{{cite book |last= Rowe-Finkbeiner|first= Kristin|date=2004|title=The F-word: Feminism in Jeopardy: Women, Politics, and the Future|url= |location= |publisher=Seal Press|page= 163-164|isbn=978-1580051149}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Expecting Better: A state-by-state analysis of parental leave programs|url=https://www.lidac.com/pdf/ParentalLeaveReportMay05.pdf|publisher=National Partnership for Women & Families|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Brief in Opposition, Nevada Department of Human Resources v. Hibbs, No. 01-1368 (U.S 2001)|url=http://scholarship.law.georgetown.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1013&context=scb|publisher=[[Georgetown University Law Center]]|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Expat adviser: Maternity leave: U.S. vs. Europe|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/23/news/23iht-radviser_ed3_.html|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref> Grant also created a national campaign for paid sick days in June 2004, which included a coalition of more than 100 organizations.<ref name="UPenn">{{cite web|title=Paid Leave Programs: A Win-Win for Employees and Employers|url=https://workfamily.sas.upenn.edu/archive/interviews/paid-leave-programs-win-win-employees-and-employers-vol76-june-2005|publisher=Work and Family Researchers Network|accessdate=30 Mar 2015}}</ref>

Grant serves as executive director of the [[Afterschool Alliance]], where she oversees all aspects of the organization—setting its goals and strategies for policies, including the re-authorization of the [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]]; working with the field to help programs tap into private and federal funding streams; and supervising research to help national, state and local afterschool advocates and providers support, create and expand quality afterschool programs. She began her duties as the executive director of the Afterschool Alliance in 2005 and has since been named one of the 25 most influential people in the afterschool field and published extensively as an afterschool expert.<ref name="NAA" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Top 25 Most Influential People in Afterschool|url=http://naaweb.org/awards-recognition/item/127-top-25-most-influential-people-in-afterschool|publisher=National AfterSchool Association|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rural kids need, deserve afterschool opportunities|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/opinion/abetteriowa/2016/04/01/rural-kids-need-deserve-afterschool-opportunities/82391662/|publisher=[[The Des Moines Register]]|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jodi Grant|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jodi-grant/|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FBI National Academy Associate Magazine, Nov/Dec 2015|url=http://www.fbinaa.org/FBINAA/Associate_Magazine/FBINAA/Associate_Matters_Archive.aspx?hkey=126ed3f2-240e-4cd0-abff-913ee0061c2e|publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] National Academy Associates|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>

